Why would we not use one?  Without one every time you wanted to add a component you would have to add a variable to the Creature Class(or whatever class owns the components) . When other people add components they could create that code outside of the Creature instead of having to modify the base class. It would keep each Components code separate from other components and separate from the  owner class. It would be much more manageable and readable code. Both Unity and Unreal do it this way and most other game engines I'm sure do it as well. We don't have to make it nearly in depth as theirs but a basic one isn't very hard to implement.

Basic sudo code below 
```
class Creature {
  std::vector<CreatureComponent> Components;

  void Update(){
      for Component in Components:
           Component->Update()

  void AddComponent()
  TCreatureComponentClass* getComponent<TComponent>()
  //etc
}

  class CreatureComponent{
    virtual void Update() = 0
  }

};
```

